    <body>
        <div class="Note">It's important remember that the disk size (the size of the EBS volume) is larger than the message spool size. <ul><li>For <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.broker_cloud_short"></MadCap:variable>s 10.6.1 and earlier, the disk requirement is twice the Message Spool size specified when you create an <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.broker_cloud_short"></MadCap:variable>. For example, if you configure an <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.broker_cloud_short"></MadCap:variable>  to use a Message Spool of 500 GiB, you require a 1 TB disk size. </li><li>For <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.broker_cloud_short"></MadCap:variable>s version 10.7.1 and later, the disk size requirement is 30% greater than the message spool size for the <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.broker_cloud_short"></MadCap:variable> class. For example, the Enterprise 250 class has a message spool size of 50 GiB, requiring a 65 GiB disk size. </li></ul>You must consider the disk space overhead when planning your Kubernetes cluster. See <MadCap:xref href="../../../../Cloud/Deployment-Considerations/resource-requirements-k8s.htm#persistent-disk-reqs" target="_blank">Volume Size for High-Availability [%=Product-Names.broker_cloud_short_title%]s</MadCap:xref> for a list of disk size requirements for all <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.broker_cloud_short" /> versions.</div>
        <p>To deploy <MadCap:variable name="Product-Names.cloud_product_short" />, you must configure the <code>StorageClass</code> in EKS to use the  <code>WaitForFirstConsumer</code> binding mode (<code>volumeBindingMode</code>). To support scale-up, the <code>StorageClass</code> must contain the <code>allowVolumeExpansion</code> property, and have it set to "<code>true</code>". You should always use XFS&#160; as the filesystem type (<code>fsType</code>).</p>
    </body>
</html>